# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-dynamodb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Werner Vogels, CTO at Amazon.com, provided a motivation for the project in his 2012 announcement.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon began as a decentralized network of services.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Originally, services had direct access to each other's databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When this became a bottleneck on engineering operations, services moved away from this direct access pattern in favor of public-facing APIs.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Still, third-party relational database management systems struggled to handle Amazon's client base.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] This culminated during the 2004 holiday season, when several technologies failed under high traffic.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Traditional databases often split data into smaller pieces to save space, but combining those pieces during searches can make queries slower.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Many of Amazon's services demanded mostly primary-key reads on their data, and with speed a top priority, putting these pieces together was extremely taxing.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Content with compromising storage efficiency, Amazon's response was Dynamo: a highly available key–value store built for internal use.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Dynamo, it seemed, was everything their engineers needed, but adoption lagged.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon's developers opted for "just works" design patterns with S3 and SimpleDB.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] While these systems had noticeable design flaws, they did not demand the overhead of provisioning hardware and scaling and re-partitioning data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon's next iteration of NoSQL technology, DynamoDB, automated these database management operations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB organizes data into tables, which are similar to spreadsheets.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each table contains items (rows), and each item is made up of attributes (columns).
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each item has a unique identifier called a primary key, which helps locate it within the table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A DynamoDB Table is a logical grouping of items, which represent the data stored in this Table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Given the NoSQL nature of DynamoDB, the Tables do not require that all items in a Table conform to some predefined schema.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] An Item in DynamoDB is a set of attributes that can be uniquely identified in a Table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] An Attribute is an atomic data entity that in itself is a Key-Value pair.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The Key is always of String type, while the value can be of one of multiple data types.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] An Item is uniquely identified in a Table using a subset of its attributes called Keys.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A Primary Key is a set of attributes that uniquely identifies items in a DynamoDB Table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Creation of a DynamoDB Table requires definition of a Primary Key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each item in a DynamoDB Table is required to have all of the attributes that constitute the Primary Key, and no two items in a Table can have the same Primary Key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Primary Keys in Dynamo DB can consist of either one or two attributes.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a Primary Key is made up of only one attribute, it is called a Partition Key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Partition Keys determine the physical location of the associated item.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In this case, no two items in a table can have the same Partition Key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a Primary Key is made up of two attributes, the first one is called a "Partition Key" and the second is called a "Sort Key".
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] As before, the Partition Key decides the physical Location of Data, but the Sort Key then decides the relative logical position of associated item's record inside that physical location.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In this case, two items in a Table can have the same Partition Key, but no two items in a partition can have the same Sort Key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In other words, a given combination of Partition Key and Sort Key is guaranteed to have at most one item associated with it in a DynamoDB Table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB supports numerical, String, Boolean, Document, and Set Data Types.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Primary Key of a Table is the Default or Primary Index of a DynamoDB Table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In addition, a DynamoDB Table can have Secondary Indices.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A Secondary Index is defined on an attribute that is different from Partition Key or Sort Key as the Primary Index.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a Secondary Index has same Partition Key as Primary Index but a different Sort Key, it is called as the Local Secondary Index.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When Primary Index and Secondary Index have different Partition Key, the Secondary index is known as the Global Secondary Index.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB data modeling patterns are architectural approaches used in Amazon DynamoDB, a NoSQL database service designed for distributed systems.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] As well as "Time-Series Design", optimized for workloads like logging and metrics, typically using a partition key for entity identification and a sort key representing timestamps to efficiently query time-based datasets.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each pattern addresses specific technical requirements.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Single Table Design" can optimize query efficiency by co-locating related data under the same partition key to reduce access latency.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Multiple Table Design" enables separation of concerns by isolating data into purpose-specific tables with distinct access patterns.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Event Sourcing" preserves a historical log of state changes, often implemented with immutable data storage.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Materialized Views" simplify complex analytical queries through pre-aggregation strategies tailored to access patterns.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] "Time-Series Design" uses partitioning and sorting strategies to efficiently store and query large volumes of temporal data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon DynamoDB's claim of single-digit millisecond latency primarily applies to simple operations such as `GetItem` and `PutItem`, which retrieve or modify individual items using their primary keys.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] This reflects the average latency under ideal conditions, such as even partition distribution and sufficient throughput provisioning, and does not account for transport overhead incurred during communication with the DynamoDB endpoint.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] More complex operations, such as `Query` with filters, `Scan`, or those involving large datasets, may experience increased latency due to additional computation and data transfer requirements.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Although DynamoDB does not natively support locking, different mechanisms exist.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Optimistic locking may use a version number to detect conflicts that occur after updates, rather than preventing them in advance.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Pessimistic locking, by contrast, may involve conditional updates with attributes such as `lockTime` and `lockedBy`.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When combined with Time to Live (TTL), these attributes enable the automated removal of expired locks, potentially enhancing concurrency management in event-driven architectures.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB uses hashing and B-trees to manage data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Upon entry, data is first distributed into different partitions by hashing on the partition key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each partition can store up to 10 GB of data and handle by default 1,000 write capacity units (WCU) and 3,000 read capacity units (RCU).
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] One RCU represents one strongly consistent read per second or two eventually consistent reads per second for items up to 4 KB in size.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] One WCU represents one write per second for an item up to 1 KB in size.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] To prevent data loss, DynamoDB features a two-tier backup system of replication and long-term storage.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each partition features three nodes, each of which contains a copy of that partition's data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Each node also contains two data structures: a B tree used to locate items, and a replication log that notes all changes made to the node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB periodically takes snapshots of these two data structures and stores them for a month in S3 so that engineers can perform point-in-time restores of their databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Within each partition, one of the three nodes is designated the "leader node".
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] All write operations travel first through the leader node before propagating, which makes writes consistent in DynamoDB.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] To maintain its status, the leader sends a "heartbeat" to each other node every 1.5 seconds.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Should another node stop receiving heartbeats, it can initiate a new leader election.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB uses the Paxos algorithm to elect leaders.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Amazon engineers originally avoided Dynamo due to engineering overheads like provisioning and managing partitions and nodes.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In response, the DynamoDB team built a service it calls AutoAdmin to manage a database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] AutoAdmin replaces a node when it stops responding by copying data from another node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] When a partition exceeds any of its three thresholds (RCU, WCU, or 10 GB), AutoAdmin will automatically add additional partitions to further segment the data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Just like indexing systems in the relational model, DynamoDB demands that any updates to a table be reflected in each of the table's indices.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB handles this using a service it calls the "log propagator", which subscribes to the replication logs in each node and sends additional Put, Update, and Delete requests to indices as necessary.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Because indices result in substantial performance hits for write requests, DynamoDB allows a user at most five of them on any given table.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Suppose that a DynamoDB user issues a write operation (a Put, Update, or Delete).
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] While a typical relational system would convert the SQL query to relational algebra and run optimization algorithms, DynamoDB skips both processes.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] There are three nodes within, each with a copy of the partition's data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The system first writes to the leader node, then writes to a second node, then sends a "success" message, and finally continues propagating to the third node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Writes are consistent because they always travel first through the leader node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Finally, the log propagator propagates the change to all indices.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] For each index, it grabs that index's primary key value from the item, then performs the same write on that index without log propagation.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] If the operation is an Update to a preexisting item, the updated attribute may serve as a primary key for an index, and thus the B tree for that index must update as well.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] B trees only handle insert, delete, and read operations, so in practice, when the log propagator receives an Update operation, it issues both a Delete operation and a Put operation to all indices.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Now suppose that a DynamoDB user issues a Get operation.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The request router proceeds as before with authentication and authorization.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Next, as above, we hash our partition key to arrive in the appropriate hash.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Now, we encounter a problem: with three nodes in eventual consistency with one another, how can we decide which to investigate?
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] DynamoDB offers the user two options when issuing a read: consistent and eventually consistent.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A consistent read visits the leader node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] But the consistency-availability trade-off rears its head again here: in read-heavy systems, always reading from the leader can overwhelm a single node and reduce availability.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] The second option, an eventually consistent read, selects a random node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] In practice, this is where DynamoDB trades consistency for availability.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] If we take this route, what are the odds of an inconsistency?
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] We'd need a write operation to return "success" and begin propagating to the third node, but not finish.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] We'd also need our Get to target this third node.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] This means a 1-in-3 chance of inconsistency within the write operation's propagation window.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] Any number of catastrophes could cause a node to fall behind, but in the vast majority of cases, the third node is up-to-date within milliseconds of the leader.
[src:aws-dynamodb/amazon-dynamodb] A race condition in a DynamoDB component triggered a 14 hour outage for Amazon's US-EAST-1 region on 19 October 2025, resulting in widespread outages of global services.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:aws-dynamodb/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:aws-dynamodb/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:aws-dynamodb/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:aws-dynamodb/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:aws-dynamodb/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
